00:00:36.524 --> 00:00:38.700
- Welcome to a Conversation with History.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:39.840
I'm Harry Kreisler of

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:41.810
the Institute of International Studies.

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:43.550
Our guest today is Neil Shubin

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:46.570
who is Provost of the Field Museum

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:50.260
as well as Robert R. Bensley,

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:54.900
Professor of Organismal
Biology and Anatomy

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:56.930
at the University of Chicago,

00:00:56.930 --> 00:00:59.470
where he serves as Associate Dean.

00:00:59.470 --> 00:01:02.580
He's the author of the
book Your Inner Fish,

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:06.610
a Journey into the 3.5
Billion-Year History

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:08.370
of the Human Body.

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:10.700
He's visiting the Berkeley campus

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:14.690
as the Hitchcock professor
in the spring of 2009.

00:01:14.690 --> 00:01:16.100
Neil, welcome to Berkeley.

00:01:16.100 --> 00:01:17.060
- Thank you.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:18.620
- Where we born and raised?

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:20.540
- I was born and raised in Philadelphia.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:23.930
- Aha, and looking back, how
do you think your parents

00:01:23.930 --> 00:01:26.470
shaped your thinking about the world,

00:01:26.470 --> 00:01:27.780
the universe, I should say.

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:30.737
- Yeah my folks, I mean, my
folks encouraged curiosity

00:01:30.737 --> 00:01:32.550
and that was the biggest thing in me.

00:01:32.550 --> 00:01:36.130
I was a sort of kid who
had a new hobby every week.

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:38.190
I would want to telescope one week,

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:40.590
rock hammer the next week,
it was always science,

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:43.120
and they encouraged me
exploring in a lot of ways.

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:45.710
And I think that, and I can trace so much

00:01:45.710 --> 00:01:47.110
of my interest in science

00:01:47.110 --> 00:01:49.540
and ultimately the way I do science

00:01:49.540 --> 00:01:52.450
to the way my parents
encouraged my curiosity.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:01:54.639
- And I assumed that
they were very supportive

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:56.410
generally, basically.

00:01:56.410 --> 00:01:58.140
- Yeah, absolutely, absolutely.

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:01.270
I mean one of the things we
always did was go to museums.

00:02:01.270 --> 00:02:03.340
And it was, you know just
our form of recreation,

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:05.290
museums, acuaria, things like that.

00:02:05.290 --> 00:02:07.870
And I just remember, you know,
looking at museum exhibits

00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:09.540
or seeing fish in the aquarium

00:02:09.540 --> 00:02:11.140
and it would just capture my imagination

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:12.160
as a young kid, you know.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:13.592
And it still does in some ways.

00:02:13.592 --> 00:02:15.070
- And what about high school?

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:17.550
Any teachers before you
were off to college?

00:02:17.550 --> 00:02:19.480
- Yeah, I had some really
excellent teachers in high school.

00:02:19.480 --> 00:02:20.990
I was really fortunate that way.

00:02:20.990 --> 00:02:23.720
What happened is actually
being in Philadelphia.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:28.340
In 1976 I was about 10th or
11th grade, something like that,

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:30.760
and that was the
bicentennial celebrations,

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:33.330
and it was a very big
deal in Philadelphia.

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:35.210
And I had a history teacher

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:37.343
who wanted us to learn archeology.

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:41.170
And he was an amateur
archaeologist himself,

00:02:41.170 --> 00:02:43.190
and he linked up with archeologists,

00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:44.880
and we were working on archeology

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.460
from of the colonial days
and it just blew my mind.

00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:51.160
That we can by digging in the dirt

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:53.240
learn something about our past, you know.

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:56.290
- So in a way you're sort
of piecing things together

00:02:56.290 --> 00:02:58.820
that would prove useful later in life.

00:02:58.820 --> 00:02:59.760
- Oh, there's no doubt, looking back,

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:01.590
that was so critical, you know.

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:03.140
- And undergraduate work?

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:07.070
- Yeah. undergrad, I went to
Columbia in New York City,

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:09.540
which was fortuitous in a lot of ways,

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:13.130
because there's the
great museum in New York,

00:03:13.130 --> 00:03:14.870
the American Museum of Natural History

00:03:14.870 --> 00:03:17.040
which was a venue that I
hung out and all the time.

00:03:17.040 --> 00:03:19.460
I even had a little office
when I was an undergrad there.

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:23.280
There was a curator who basically
set me up with an office.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:24.600
He saw I was a curious kid,

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:26.210
set me up with an office, a library card,

00:03:26.210 --> 00:03:27.440
and keys to the collection.

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:29.263
And he didn't ask
anything of me other than

00:03:29.263 --> 00:03:30.810
just go explore.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:35.080
It was really remarkable,
what an opportunity that was.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:37.490
But when I was at in college

00:03:37.490 --> 00:03:39.037
I was interested in biology,

00:03:39.037 --> 00:03:41.480
that's where I really got
interested in biology.

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:43.410
I was started with an
interest in archeology,

00:03:43.410 --> 00:03:44.883
but then shifted to biology.

00:03:45.773 --> 00:03:48.710
It soon became clear that
if I wanted to bridge

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:50.980
my interest in archeology
with my interest in biology,

00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:54.240
paleontology, (chuckles)
not a bad way to go.

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:55.857
- And is that what you majored
in as an undergraduate?

00:03:55.857 --> 00:03:58.550
- No, I majored in anthropology, biology,

00:03:58.550 --> 00:03:59.750
and I minored in geology.

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:01.610
So there was no paleontology major,

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:04.160
I sorta cut and pasted a lot of stuff.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.280
- And are you already seeing connections

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:12.510
or were connections being
made between these disciplines

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:14.430
as you took them as an undergraduate

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:15.950
and then as a graduate student?

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:17.070
- I see it in retrospect.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:18.340
At the time I wasn't seeing it,

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:20.340
but definitely in retrospect
I see how those connections

00:04:20.340 --> 00:04:22.720
were sitting probably in
my subconscious in some way

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:24.900
and influencing my behavior.

00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:27.130
Because I was also very
interested in history as well,

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:30.290
American history, classical
history and things like that.

00:04:30.290 --> 00:04:33.890
So all these different tendrils
were sort of coming together

00:04:33.890 --> 00:04:36.980
in paleontology, evolutionary biology.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:38.330
- And then on to graduate school,

00:04:38.330 --> 00:04:39.820
and where did you do your graduate work?

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:41.980
- In Boston, at Harvard.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:46.220
And I entered Harvard wanting
to work on fossil mammals

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:49.370
and understand how mammals
diversified, you know,

00:04:49.370 --> 00:04:51.100
why if some mammals that climb trees,

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:52.683
others that dig, and so forth.

00:04:52.683 --> 00:04:56.270
And then by about the second
year, switched to fish.

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:57.320
For a lot of reasons.

00:04:58.432 --> 00:05:00.350
Fish and amphibians.

00:05:00.350 --> 00:05:01.900
'Cause there are some fundamental problems

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:03.630
I wanted to get at.

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:04.880
And Harvard was another good choice,

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:08.390
because like Berkeley
actually, it's a big university

00:05:08.390 --> 00:05:10.650
that has a museum embedded inside of it.

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:15.020
And so, again, it's linking
from museum to the laboratory,

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:17.474
that's always been
something that I've done

00:05:17.474 --> 00:05:18.510
and cherished, actually.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:20.490
You know, a museum has
always been important to me.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:24.030
- It's interesting because when you think

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:27.710
of museums and libraries,
you don't think of

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:32.660
adventurers, which seems to
be a part of your personality

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:33.870
as we get into your work.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:36.240
Or is that not fair, is
that not a fair statement?

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:37.350
- Well it's right to think on that way,

00:05:37.350 --> 00:05:39.070
but I think that's a miss.

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:41.180
Because that's where the adventures begin.

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:43.630
The adventures begin opening
a cabinet in a museum,

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:45.730
seeing some specimens,
trying to figure out

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:48.100
the problems that those
specimens show you.

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:50.230
It begins in a library
where you're figuring out

00:05:50.230 --> 00:05:52.420
where to work in the field and so forth.

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.200
So my starting point is
always a library or a museum

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.070
because they're revealing
to me the problems,

00:05:57.070 --> 00:05:59.580
the puzzles, you know, that needs solving.

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:00.960
- And then, at Harvard,

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:02.750
what did you do your dissertation on?

00:06:02.750 --> 00:06:04.450
- I worked on the
development and evolution

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:08.230
of the limb, arms and legs,
and I came up with a theory

00:06:08.230 --> 00:06:12.000
of the relationship between
arms and legs and fins and fish.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.030
So sort of the transformation
of fins to limbs.

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:16.800
Looking at embryology,
how organisms develop,

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:19.100
and looking at fossils,
so I was trying to link

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:21.603
my biology and paleontology interests.

00:06:23.967 --> 00:06:28.640
- So let's talk about what
you are as a scientist.

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:33.640
I guess you are both an
anatomist and a paleontologist,

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:36.310
and so let's go down that road.

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:40.980
What are the skill sets that you think are

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:45.420
required to do these fields well?

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:47.453
- Well there's the personal skill set

00:06:47.453 --> 00:06:49.560
and then there's the scientific skills,

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:52.055
intellectual skillset, I'll
call it intellectual, really.

00:06:52.055 --> 00:06:55.820
The personal skill set is you
have to be pretty patient.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:57.210
(chuckles)

00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:59.590
You have to be able to
sort of sit with a problem

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:02.120
long enough to find an answer.

00:07:02.120 --> 00:07:04.490
Curiosity helps, 'cause
that's what drives you

00:07:04.490 --> 00:07:07.463
and that's the fuel, is
curiosity and has always been.

00:07:08.530 --> 00:07:10.211
The intellectual skill
set I think really is

00:07:10.211 --> 00:07:12.630
you know, understanding
the structure of the body.

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:15.170
Knowing the names of
the hulls and the bones

00:07:15.170 --> 00:07:18.610
and the bumps and the nerves
and all that sort of stuff.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:20.430
Knowing quite a bit about genetics

00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:22.400
but that's sort of critical nowadays,

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:26.100
how genes are inherited
and how they specify

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:28.223
pattern and anatomy and so forth.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:31.560
And basically I think the other big piece

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:33.900
of the skill set, and this
is just sort of generic,

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:36.120
is the willingness

00:07:37.638 --> 00:07:39.180
and lack of fear

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:42.600
to enter new fields and
to learn new disciplines.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:45.220
I mean, the way I look at my field

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:50.040
is not as a separate
silo, as one discipline.

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:52.750
I really look at it as a
puzzle or a problem to solve.

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:55.560
And if you look at it as a
puzzle or a problem to solve

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:58.180
different disciplines become tools to you.

00:07:58.180 --> 00:08:01.930
And so if you can somehow figure out

00:08:01.930 --> 00:08:03.770
how to gain access to
those tools even though

00:08:03.770 --> 00:08:05.730
they might be in another
field like geology

00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:08.143
or or chemistry or something like that,

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:11.800
you will be better off at the end and able

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:13.780
in your ability to solve your problem.

00:08:13.780 --> 00:08:15.140
So I think one of the
most important things

00:08:15.140 --> 00:08:16.470
particularly in today's science

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:19.080
is the ability and desire
to collaborate or learn

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:23.000
and extend one's toolkit
to different disciplines.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:24.257
- You write in your book, you say,

00:08:24.257 --> 00:08:27.480
"the unknown should not
be a source of suspicion,

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:30.670
fear, or retreat to superstition,

00:08:30.670 --> 00:08:33.840
but motivation to
continue asking questions

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:35.377
and seeking answers".

00:08:35.377 --> 00:08:38.433
So you really have to be comfortable

00:08:38.433 --> 00:08:40.800
with moving across fields.

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:42.750
- And taking a leap into the unknown.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:44.550
You know, when you set off an experiment

00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:46.200
or a new expedition or something,

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:47.800
there's no guarantee of success.

00:08:49.290 --> 00:08:52.520
There's a level of risk-taking
that's in this as well.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:54.670
I mean, scientists are
always taking risks.

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:57.410
Sometimes for quite bold ones.

00:08:59.617 --> 00:09:02.780
It is about finding answers to questions

00:09:02.780 --> 00:09:05.555
and then ultimately, being
able to ask better questions,

00:09:05.555 --> 00:09:06.410
(laughing) you know.

00:09:06.410 --> 00:09:07.920
The questions don't stop,
they just get better

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:11.800
hopefully, or more refined,
hopefully, if you're successful.

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:15.593
I was a child of Apollo, the
rocket, not the Greek god.

00:09:17.137 --> 00:09:18.861
(both laughing)

00:09:18.861 --> 00:09:21.080
When I was 14, you know, 10 to 14,

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:23.800
that's when the missions
were going to the moon.

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:25.100
You know, that blew my mind.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:27.840
That humanity can design a contraption

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:30.560
that takes people to the
moon and back, you know

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:33.520
and the ability to do that
still chokes me up to this day.

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:34.370
It's really cool.

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:40.540
- And in this context,
where do you see creativity?

00:09:41.656 --> 00:09:45.163
How would you characterize creativity?

00:09:45.999 --> 00:09:48.250
Is it something that that flows

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:51.330
from being on top of
all of these disciplines

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.360
and being comfortable with the tools

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:55.010
that you just described?

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:59.635
- Creativity comes to us, I
mean, it's hard to capture.

00:09:59.635 --> 00:10:02.890
I think for me creativity
comes at the moments

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:05.250
when I'm able to throw off the constraints

00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:08.590
of some of my previous
thinking, but not so much

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:10.480
that I'm not throwing
away to what I've learned.

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:11.313
You know what I'm saying?

00:10:11.313 --> 00:10:13.800
It's it's sort of trying
to see things in a new way

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:17.100
that was that was sort of
invisible to me before.

00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:19.710
Because of maybe mental traps I was in,

00:10:19.710 --> 00:10:23.770
or preconceived notions that
are expectations that I have.

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:25.760
And the more I can get away from those ,

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:27.680
the more I can think in new ways

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:30.560
and do something truly creative, you know.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:32.436
And so to me it really comes down to

00:10:32.436 --> 00:10:35.790
trying to get rid of some
of your preconceived notions

00:10:35.790 --> 00:10:37.790
and expectations and
always challenging them.

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:40.150
And we're not always good at that,

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:42.210
but I think that's how advances happened.

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:44.330
- Now you had a fellowship at Berkeley

00:10:44.330 --> 00:10:48.130
or the Miller fellowship, and
I think you said yesterday

00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:52.912
in your lecture that this was
a moment in your education

00:10:52.912 --> 00:10:57.851
that was very helpful in
broadening your perspective

00:10:57.851 --> 00:11:02.016
and looking at these problems in the way

00:11:02.016 --> 00:11:04.370
that integrative biology does.

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:05.203
- Yeah, very much.

00:11:05.203 --> 00:11:06.036
I mean, remember I said, you know,

00:11:06.036 --> 00:11:08.093
when I see the world as a set of problems

00:11:08.093 --> 00:11:10.292
and different disciplines
are tools to answer

00:11:10.292 --> 00:11:12.270
and help tackle those problems.

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.570
When I dropped off in
Berkeley as a Miller fellow,

00:11:14.570 --> 00:11:16.250
you know, here I was in
Berkeley with a bunch of people

00:11:16.250 --> 00:11:17.960
who look the world the same way.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:18.920
It was really remarkable.

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:21.820
And so I fed off their sort
of intellectual curiosity,

00:11:21.820 --> 00:11:25.187
and energy, and interdisciplinary
approach to science

00:11:25.187 --> 00:11:26.603
and intellectual questions.

00:11:28.839 --> 00:11:32.560
- Now, you are doing your work

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:34.450
at a time when there really, just

00:11:37.190 --> 00:11:41.370
many, many breakthroughs
across fields, basically.

00:11:41.370 --> 00:11:43.463
And you talk about that.

00:11:44.863 --> 00:11:48.970
So, it's an exciting time to be doing

00:11:48.970 --> 00:11:53.410
what you're doing because of
the developments in genetics,

00:11:53.410 --> 00:11:56.460
the developments in information
technology and so on.

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:57.470
- Hugely so.

00:11:57.470 --> 00:12:00.450
I'm asking questions or able
to answer questions today

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:02.457
that I wasn't even thinking about

00:12:02.457 --> 00:12:05.130
10 years ago, five years ago.

00:12:05.130 --> 00:12:06.930
I mean the pace of change is so rapid.

00:12:06.930 --> 00:12:08.900
Yet we're still, what's beautiful,

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:11.800
is to be able to apply new
techniques, new approaches

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:13.700
to sort of the classical problems,

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:14.840
the questions that have been around

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:16.450
for long periods of times,

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:18.930
that excited anatomist in the 1800's,

00:12:18.930 --> 00:12:21.760
to be able to address those
fundamental questions.

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:23.500
That's where the real thrill is, you know.

00:12:23.500 --> 00:12:27.563
And when you're able to do
that, it's just so satisfying.

00:12:29.455 --> 00:12:33.617
- And in your book, you
talk about your experiences

00:12:34.850 --> 00:12:38.773
and lecturing medical
students about human anatomy.

00:12:39.859 --> 00:12:43.823
So this is, I would presume that

00:12:45.930 --> 00:12:49.100
in a previous generation,
were paleontologists

00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:49.933
teaching in medical school?

00:12:49.933 --> 00:12:51.630
- Yeah, from time to time they were.

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:53.903
Yeah, it wasn't highly unusual.

00:12:53.903 --> 00:12:56.260
In fact, as you know,
to be a paleontologist

00:12:56.260 --> 00:12:58.060
you have to be a pretty good anatomist.

00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:01.210
And you know, paleo anthropologists,
it's routine for them

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:03.408
to be involved in anatomy departments.

00:13:03.408 --> 00:13:06.050
Fish paleontologists like
myself, or amphibian ones,

00:13:06.050 --> 00:13:07.577
it's not as often.

00:13:07.577 --> 00:13:09.500
But it's not that much of a stretch.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:12.479
I remember when I started
teaching human anatomy

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:15.430
the students would come
to me and they'd say,

00:13:15.430 --> 00:13:18.034
Dr. Shubin, what kind of doctor are you?

00:13:18.034 --> 00:13:19.275
(both laughing)

00:13:19.275 --> 00:13:20.108
Let's see, are you a surgeon

00:13:20.108 --> 00:13:20.941
or are you a cardiologist or something?

00:13:20.941 --> 00:13:22.440
I said, well, I'm a fish paleontologist.

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:23.970
He's like, I want my money back.

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:24.803
- A fish doctor

00:13:24.803 --> 00:13:26.620
- Yeah, right, he's like,
I want my money back

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:27.570
or something like that.

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:28.580
But it became pretty clear,

00:13:28.580 --> 00:13:30.090
as you can begin to teach the course,

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:32.870
that being a paleontologist,
an embryologist,

00:13:32.870 --> 00:13:35.290
a fish paleontologist, in particular,

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:37.380
actually offers a nice
roadmap to the human body.

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:39.990
So became pretty, pretty
powerful actually.

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:43.765
- And now you, in your work, you have made

00:13:43.765 --> 00:13:47.174
an important discovery and this came,

00:13:47.174 --> 00:13:49.130
and we'll talk about that in a minute,

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:53.820
because at some point you
decided you were interested

00:13:53.820 --> 00:13:57.830
in these periods of revolution in

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:02.950
the evolution of animals and man.

00:14:02.950 --> 00:14:05.320
Talk about that interest
and where it came from.

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:06.830
- Sure, if you look at the history of life

00:14:06.830 --> 00:14:09.290
there are certain moments
where it seems like

00:14:09.290 --> 00:14:12.780
revolutions in the air, where
major changes are happening.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:14.260
In the origin of body plans

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:16.740
or the origin of diverse kinds of fish,

00:14:16.740 --> 00:14:19.845
the origin of different kinds
of creatures we call reptiles,

00:14:19.845 --> 00:14:23.820
you know, things like that.

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:25.900
Seeing those periods helps me choose

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:28.386
the intervals to work
on as a paleontologist.

00:14:28.386 --> 00:14:30.570
And so I work on Devonian age rocks,

00:14:30.570 --> 00:14:35.320
which are rocks about 365 to
380 or so million years old,

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:37.150
of that portion of the Devonian.

00:14:37.150 --> 00:14:39.400
And I do that because that's
when a lot of groups of fish

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:41.550
first came about,
including fish with legs.

00:14:43.423 --> 00:14:45.930
And then also work on rocks
about 200 million years old,

00:14:45.930 --> 00:14:48.010
because that's when
different kinds of creatures

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:50.340
we call reptiles came
about, including mammals

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:52.832
and crocodiles and dinosaurs

00:14:52.832 --> 00:14:55.450
and all kinds of different
kinds of amphibians.

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:57.600
So, those have always attracted me

00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:59.570
because when you run a field expedition

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:00.940
in one of those intervals,

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:02.290
there's always the chance
of finding something

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:04.740
that will tell you about one
of these great transformations,

00:15:04.740 --> 00:15:05.990
these great transitions.

00:15:05.990 --> 00:15:07.860
- You quote Eisenhower in your book

00:15:07.860 --> 00:15:09.860
who said, "in preparing for battle,

00:15:09.860 --> 00:15:12.570
I have found that planning is essential

00:15:12.570 --> 00:15:15.140
but plans are useless".

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:16.290
- Yeah, 'cause there's always, I mean.

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:19.330
So take working in the
Arctic, for example.

00:15:19.330 --> 00:15:21.080
I plan like crazy to work up there.

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:25.010
With my colleagues, you
know Ted and Garish,

00:15:25.010 --> 00:15:26.404
who we planned together.

00:15:26.404 --> 00:15:29.700
We plan the expeditions
down to the last candy bar.

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:32.360
You know, all the food goes
up there and everything.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:33.580
- You better bring them, my guess,

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:36.274
'cause it's cold up there (both chuckling)

00:15:36.274 --> 00:15:38.514
and the nearest town is not San Francisco.

00:15:38.514 --> 00:15:41.681
- Exactly, and that's your
entertainment, you know.

00:15:41.681 --> 00:15:43.113
So it's a good idea.

00:15:44.130 --> 00:15:45.790
Yet, you know I make all these plans,

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:47.650
we do all this, and have move days,

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.227
and plan when the helicopters
are gonna get there

00:15:49.227 --> 00:15:50.650
and so forth, but at some point

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:51.930
you have to throw the plans away,

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:54.380
because the facts on the
ground change everything.

00:15:54.380 --> 00:15:55.470
You have to be flexible.

00:15:55.470 --> 00:15:58.050
The weather, mechanical may be bad,

00:15:58.050 --> 00:15:59.860
there may be mechanical problems.

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:01.710
You may discover something in one place

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:02.990
and want to stay there longer,

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:05.300
or not be discovering something in a place

00:16:05.300 --> 00:16:06.620
you had high hopes for.

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:09.120
So you have to retain
a degree of flexibility

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:10.680
as the facts on the ground change.

00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:14.330
And the only way you can be
effective and be flexible

00:16:14.330 --> 00:16:17.010
is to plan like crazy, I
mean you need that sort of

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:19.930
knowledge of all the parameters

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:21.909
and planning helps you do that.

00:16:21.909 --> 00:16:24.233
But you have to throw them away. (laughs)

00:16:25.150 --> 00:16:28.480
- And you, and I want to
get the name right here,

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:31.340
your great breakthrough

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:34.660
was the discovery of tiktaalik,

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:39.320
a large freshwater fish
that had characteristics

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:44.470
that tell us it was a transitional figure

00:16:44.470 --> 00:16:47.111
in the movement from fish to land.

00:16:47.111 --> 00:16:52.000
Let's walk through that,
and in being interested

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.860
in these great periods of transformation

00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:59.163
and you turn to geology first,

00:17:00.122 --> 00:17:03.100
and geology tells you a lot

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:04.960
about where you want to look.

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:07.420
- Oh absolutely, I mean, we work at home,

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:09.570
in libraries, you know,
or on the internet,

00:17:10.978 --> 00:17:13.200
or in the internet to
try to find places to go.

00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:14.720
We have a time period in mind,

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:16.470
and the sort of the biggest parameter

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:18.000
to think about first is what age rocks

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:19.280
you're gonna work on.

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:21.176
And that's really kind of
what drove us to think about

00:17:21.176 --> 00:17:23.940
finding tiktaalik, was that when we look

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:26.090
at what we knew about in the record

00:17:26.090 --> 00:17:30.380
of fish evolving features
that allow their descendants

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:33.500
to walk on land, it came
out there's a sort of gap

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:37.253
in our knowledge in rocks
around 375 million years old.

00:17:38.140 --> 00:17:40.610
So that sort of insight
was really critical.

00:17:40.610 --> 00:17:42.294
Then it became clear
that we had to find rocks

00:17:42.294 --> 00:17:44.550
of the right type, places in the world

00:17:44.550 --> 00:17:48.980
that had rocks of the right
type to find fossil fish.

00:17:48.980 --> 00:17:52.830
And then, you know, with
that screen or that filter

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:54.920
we would look at geological maps.

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:57.502
We would look at aerial photos

00:17:57.502 --> 00:18:00.530
and then try to figure out where to go.

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:02.297
- And even college
textbooks for one thing.

00:18:02.297 --> 00:18:03.130
- Well that's what I was saying,

00:18:03.130 --> 00:18:03.963
so I applied all these great things,

00:18:03.963 --> 00:18:05.950
and we were looking at geological
maps and all this stuff.

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:08.380
And had some ideas, but
the ultimate insight

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:10.140
that led to the discovery of tiktaalik

00:18:10.140 --> 00:18:12.330
came from a college geology textbook

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:15.310
and showed me an area, and Ted Daeschler,

00:18:15.310 --> 00:18:17.097
who I've been working with for years,

00:18:17.097 --> 00:18:19.650
it showed me, it showed Ted and I,

00:18:19.650 --> 00:18:22.320
an area we hadn't even
considered before. (chuckling)

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:25.090
- But in the beginning, with no budget,

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:30.010
you were actually, you had a
comparable area, fortunately,

00:18:30.010 --> 00:18:33.460
in the state of Pennsylvania
where you were teaching.

00:18:33.460 --> 00:18:34.293
- Yeah, exactly/

00:18:34.293 --> 00:18:37.130
- So you could you could go
down the road, so to speak.

00:18:37.130 --> 00:18:38.550
- Oh literally, yeah, and spend, you know,

00:18:38.550 --> 00:18:41.400
20 bucks on a field
expedition driving from a car.

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:42.680
And that was productive,

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.530
but those rocks were sort
of too young to produce

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:46.630
a tiktaalik like creature.

00:18:46.630 --> 00:18:47.980
We were already finding limbed animals

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:50.006
that were fairly far along.

00:18:50.006 --> 00:18:50.839
- Right

00:18:50.839 --> 00:18:51.680
- You know. and so we had to move back

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:53.330
about 10 million years in time

00:18:53.330 --> 00:18:55.610
and that's when the search
for a new area began

00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:57.488
in about the mid '90s.

00:18:57.488 --> 00:19:00.970
And then we sort of ran into
this college geology textbook

00:19:00.970 --> 00:19:03.600
during an argument, actually,
in my office in Philadelphia.

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:05.930
We ran into this
undergraduate geology textbook

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:08.940
and found that the Canadian Arctic

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:13.303
had enormous amounts of exposed
Rock of just the right age.

00:19:14.210 --> 00:19:18.679
- Now it's very clear that
in your work serendipity,

00:19:18.679 --> 00:19:22.620
is also at play, which
we haven't mentioned yet,

00:19:22.620 --> 00:19:26.258
and when you chose the site

00:19:26.258 --> 00:19:29.730
for the the kinds of formation of rocks,

00:19:29.730 --> 00:19:33.220
which were accessible, and
the rocks were from the period

00:19:33.220 --> 00:19:34.853
that you were interested in,

00:19:36.479 --> 00:19:38.650
you had an undergraduate assistant

00:19:38.650 --> 00:19:43.650
who began this discovery, in a sense,

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:46.690
by being late returning back to camp,

00:19:46.690 --> 00:19:47.960
but tell us about that.

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:51.160
- Yeah, what happened was
we had a college student

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:53.750
who wanted to learn
paleontology named Jason Downs,

00:19:53.750 --> 00:19:56.130
University of Pennsylvania
at the time, he was a senior.

00:19:56.130 --> 00:19:57.693
And he came along with us.

00:20:00.132 --> 00:20:03.520
Jason, he somehow got separated
from the team this day.

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:05.037
We all went back to prepare dinner,

00:20:05.037 --> 00:20:07.930
it was around 7:00 and there was no Jason.

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:08.830
And that's a worry.

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:11.480
When someone gets separated
and dinner rolls around,

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:12.313
and you're not seeing them,

00:20:12.313 --> 00:20:15.260
that's when you begin to
worry if they're in trouble.

00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:18.080
Maybe they hurt themselves,
sprained their ankle somewhere.

00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:21.124
The Arctic's a big place, and
if they're if they're hurt

00:20:21.124 --> 00:20:22.350
it would be a challenge.

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:24.380
- And you actually go out
on your own, basically.

00:20:24.380 --> 00:20:25.470
- Well, we usually go out in groups of two

00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:26.790
that was the weird thing about this.

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:28.680
I mean, you're not
supposed to get separated.

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:29.760
And Jason got separated.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:30.660
- I see.

00:20:30.660 --> 00:20:33.666
- And so we were beginning to worry

00:20:33.666 --> 00:20:36.807
and then we heard footsteps,
you know coming to the tent.

00:20:36.807 --> 00:20:37.640
(vocalizing zipping)

00:20:37.640 --> 00:20:38.473
Tent opens up and there's Jason.

00:20:38.473 --> 00:20:40.260
His eyes are like orbs,
you know. (chuckles)

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:41.093
He's out of breath.

00:20:41.093 --> 00:20:43.280
We worried that Jason's being chased

00:20:43.280 --> 00:20:44.680
by a polar bear or what have you.

00:20:44.680 --> 00:20:47.230
But the real reason became clear

00:20:47.230 --> 00:20:48.470
why he was so excited and late

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:50.740
was every pocket of
his parka and his pants

00:20:50.740 --> 00:20:53.290
was filled with fossil fish bones.

00:20:53.290 --> 00:20:55.200
What happened is during that absence

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:58.768
he had discovered a
layer of rock that was,

00:20:58.768 --> 00:21:02.746
contained like a carpet
of fossil fish bones.

00:21:02.746 --> 00:21:05.220
So then, you know after talking to Jason,

00:21:05.220 --> 00:21:08.010
after he'd calmed a bit and
told us where the area was,

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:11.630
we decided, it's the Arctic,
it's daylight 24 hours a day,

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:13.120
You know, dinner can wait.

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:14.580
We grab the candy bars. (chuckles)

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:17.110
And off we went to Jason's little site.

00:21:17.110 --> 00:21:19.268
To look for the layer and try to map it.

00:21:19.268 --> 00:21:22.820
And it took us a while to find the layer,

00:21:22.820 --> 00:21:24.300
took quite a while, actually.

00:21:24.300 --> 00:21:25.950
And then when we did, it
turns out it was skeleton.

00:21:25.950 --> 00:21:27.890
And that layer was produced by,

00:21:27.890 --> 00:21:30.900
That layer of fish bone
fragments was produced by,

00:21:30.900 --> 00:21:33.540
skeleton after skeleton of fossil fish

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:34.490
weathering out of the rocks.

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:35.590
So it was really neat.

00:21:36.725 --> 00:21:40.710
- And, the discovery was
made on a subsequent trip?

00:21:40.710 --> 00:21:41.725
You went back, yeah.

00:21:41.725 --> 00:21:42.920
- Yeah, several years later, actually.

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:44.250
Nothing happened easy there.

00:21:44.250 --> 00:21:46.880
It took us about six
years to find tiktaalik.

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:49.591
It took us a while to really hone in.

00:21:49.591 --> 00:21:52.200
Jason's site, we had to
work it for two years

00:21:52.200 --> 00:21:54.000
before we found anything really important.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.480
- And was your fish
found at that same site?

00:21:58.480 --> 00:21:59.313
Yeah, right.

00:22:00.365 --> 00:22:04.830
And so what, do you
demarcate the site and then

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:09.172
it remains secure during these?

00:22:09.172 --> 00:22:10.362
- Yeah, you're in the
middle of nowhere, yeah.

00:22:10.362 --> 00:22:11.195
You're in the middle of
nowhere, nobody's gonna

00:22:11.195 --> 00:22:12.560
see, find it.

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:13.890
They'd have to really spend a ton of money

00:22:13.890 --> 00:22:15.003
and time to get to it.

00:22:16.260 --> 00:22:18.560
And it's also specialized.

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:19.610
There's no, really, there's no fear

00:22:19.610 --> 00:22:21.576
of somebody working that site and finding

00:22:21.576 --> 00:22:25.223
and they'd have to know,
really, some detailed geology.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:27.880
I could take someone
to that site right now

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:29.700
and show it to them, and
they still wouldn't know

00:22:29.700 --> 00:22:30.827
where the layers, you know.

00:22:30.827 --> 00:22:31.900
You have to work there for a while

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:33.800
to really get the nuance of what the rock

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:35.807
and, what the difference
between rock and fossil is,

00:22:35.807 --> 00:22:36.970
and so forth.

00:22:36.970 --> 00:22:40.410
- So the discovery is
made in the sense that,

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:45.410
hey, this is a place to look, over time,

00:22:45.660 --> 00:22:50.660
and then the, on the return
trips, you're carefully

00:22:50.994 --> 00:22:53.560
digging in to go down.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:56.120
- And so you're exposing
it as a big platform

00:22:56.120 --> 00:22:58.360
a flat bed, if you will.

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:01.800
And on that bed were skeletons,
some partial, some complete,

00:23:01.800 --> 00:23:03.050
you know, some on top of one another,

