some mushed against each other.

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:07.453
And as we did it, we
weren't finding anything,

00:23:08.328 --> 00:23:10.530
you know, truly important.

00:23:10.530 --> 00:23:12.070
I mean, they were interesting,

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:14.040
they're telling us something
about the ecosystem,

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:15.780
but it took us a while, there
was a lot of frustration.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:18.870
You know, and part of it, you
know, part of this serendipity

00:23:18.870 --> 00:23:21.320
taking over here is
being persistent enough

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:22.190
to let that happen.

00:23:22.190 --> 00:23:23.023
- [Harry] I see, right.

00:23:23.023 --> 00:23:26.160
- You know, and we made
the conscious decision

00:23:26.160 --> 00:23:28.050
to stick on this site for a period of,

00:23:28.050 --> 00:23:29.940
a long period of time.

00:23:29.940 --> 00:23:31.203
You know, several years.

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:35.610
We, in fact, the year we
ended up finding tiktaalik,

00:23:35.610 --> 00:23:38.850
which was 2004, I remember a conversation

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:40.160
three months before we went to the field

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:41.462
with Ted and Garish,

00:23:41.462 --> 00:23:42.950
really starting asking the question,

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:44.290
do we really want to go this year?

00:23:44.290 --> 00:23:46.376
I mean, have we done it enough?

00:23:46.376 --> 00:23:49.450
And we all decided no,
no, one more go, you know.

00:23:49.450 --> 00:23:50.710
And that's.

00:23:50.710 --> 00:23:54.030
- Now what you're finding on the top,

00:23:54.030 --> 00:23:57.170
is it different kinds of fishes

00:23:57.170 --> 00:24:00.751
or pieces that you can't
make anything out of it?

00:24:00.751 --> 00:24:05.140
And as you go down, are you going

00:24:05.140 --> 00:24:10.140
into earlier or different
years, basically in the layers?

00:24:10.624 --> 00:24:11.963
- This is actually one layer.

00:24:11.963 --> 00:24:15.040
And so we expose that one
single layer as a giant bed.

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:17.870
And it's all kinds of
different species of fish.

00:24:17.870 --> 00:24:19.790
There may be 10 to 15 species of fish

00:24:19.790 --> 00:24:20.940
coming out of this layer.

00:24:20.940 --> 00:24:25.630
None of them horribly
novel for that time period.

00:24:25.630 --> 00:24:27.600
You know, and so we're
finding lots of fish,

00:24:27.600 --> 00:24:29.420
and lots of different species of fish,

00:24:29.420 --> 00:24:31.813
but nothing like
tiktaalik, nothing at that,

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:36.380
part of the Tree of Life, you know.

00:24:36.380 --> 00:24:38.120
- But they are all from the same period?

00:24:38.120 --> 00:24:38.953
- Yeah

00:24:38.953 --> 00:24:39.786
- Basically?

00:24:39.786 --> 00:24:41.280
Now in finding them and saying,

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:44.120
oh there's, you know, X,

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:45.920
or oh there's Y,

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:49.351
that propels you forward
because it's telling you

00:24:49.351 --> 00:24:52.140
that the question mark
may be somewhere there.

00:24:52.140 --> 00:24:54.730
- Yeah, exactly, and then
when we, once we know

00:24:54.730 --> 00:24:56.530
what tiktaalik looks like,

00:24:56.530 --> 00:24:58.670
and that gives you confidence

00:24:58.670 --> 00:25:00.190
that when you go somewhere else

00:25:00.190 --> 00:25:01.960
your eye will be a little more trained

00:25:01.960 --> 00:25:02.840
to find it if it's there.

00:25:02.840 --> 00:25:04.900
Then we have it from a
couple other sites as well.

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:08.280
- Now how did you know what
tiktaalik would look like?

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:11.149
You hypothesized it, yeah.

00:25:11.149 --> 00:25:12.550
- Basically, if you look at the transition

00:25:12.550 --> 00:25:15.300
from a low fin fish to
an early limbed animal,

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:16.720
you know, you'll see,
you go from a creature

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:18.850
with a conical head with
eyes on either side,

00:25:18.850 --> 00:25:20.280
and the lobe finned fish?

00:25:20.280 --> 00:25:22.420
These early limbed animals
so a flathead sort of thing

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:23.380
with eyes on top.

00:25:23.380 --> 00:25:25.010
There're other changes as well.

00:25:25.010 --> 00:25:27.280
So we knew if we had a
flat-headed fish with scales

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:28.390
it was gonna be really interesting.

00:25:28.390 --> 00:25:30.863
That's exactly what we found,
saw for the first time,

00:25:30.863 --> 00:25:32.830
and that's when we knew we had tiktaalik.

00:25:32.830 --> 00:25:35.587
when we saw a flat-headed
fish, it was very serious.

00:25:35.587 --> 00:25:38.690
- And how did, can you
talk about that moment

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:40.841
when you saw him and

00:25:40.841 --> 00:25:43.330
what were your feelings?

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:44.163
- Well they're really beautiful

00:25:44.163 --> 00:25:45.707
and we discovered several of them,

00:25:45.707 --> 00:25:47.900
on the forth day of that season,

00:25:47.900 --> 00:25:49.700
that we almost decided not to go on.

00:25:52.218 --> 00:25:54.280
And, my colleague Steve
Gatsey is a professor at Brown

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:55.710
was working with us that year.

00:25:55.710 --> 00:25:59.590
And we were working Jason's
site, cracking rocks.

00:25:59.590 --> 00:26:01.097
And Steve says hey guys, what's this?

00:26:01.097 --> 00:26:02.690
And we all sort of ran up.

00:26:02.690 --> 00:26:05.320
And, the head of a flat
headed fish, just sticking

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:07.970
right out of the side
of the hill, you know.

00:26:07.970 --> 00:26:10.400
At that moment, we knew, it was exactly

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:11.233
what we were looking for.

00:26:11.233 --> 00:26:12.870
We didn't know how much of
the skeleton would be there,

00:26:12.870 --> 00:26:14.916
but we knew it was the exact creature.

00:26:14.916 --> 00:26:18.090
It was really, that moment was remarkable

00:26:18.090 --> 00:26:20.555
because it took us six
years to get to that point.

00:26:20.555 --> 00:26:23.595
Six years of blood, seat
and tears in the Arctic.

00:26:23.595 --> 00:26:27.350
You know, it's hard working
there, both personally

00:26:27.350 --> 00:26:29.320
and physically and financially.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:30.560
You know, you name it.

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:32.400
And so everybody who was involved

00:26:32.400 --> 00:26:34.770
in the project from the start,
who saw it at that point,

00:26:34.770 --> 00:26:36.067
it was a huge moment for us.

00:26:36.067 --> 00:26:37.910
The there was a (giggles), that moment

00:26:37.910 --> 00:26:42.100
went to panic, however, because
getting the rock fossils

00:26:42.100 --> 00:26:45.070
out of the Arctic,
particularly heavy things

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:46.440
and big things like titaalik.

00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:48.280
I mean titaalik, the biggest specimens are

00:26:48.280 --> 00:26:51.113
about nine feet long, is no small matter.

00:26:53.182 --> 00:26:55.960
And our worry shifted,
not how we are gonna

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:57.030
find these things, to how are we gonna

00:26:57.030 --> 00:26:59.016
get them out of the rock and back home,

00:26:59.016 --> 00:27:02.120
because that year we
had really bad weather.

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:05.150
Pretty much every day it
snowed or sleeted on us

00:27:05.150 --> 00:27:08.130
- Everyday and it's not
really conducive for,

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:08.963
- [Harry] Yeah

00:27:08.963 --> 00:27:09.979
- glue working on things or plasters

00:27:09.979 --> 00:27:12.100
and the traditional methods we use.

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:15.690
- So is the idea that you take the whole

00:27:15.690 --> 00:27:18.340
area around the fish out, yeah?

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:21.241
- Wrap it in plaster
and then back it comes.

00:27:21.241 --> 00:27:23.720
- [Harry] And transport it, is that also

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:24.553
a concern, I take it?

00:27:24.553 --> 00:27:25.580
- Yeah, 'cause then I need the helicopter.

00:27:25.580 --> 00:27:27.250
And so, that's why it has to be, you know.

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:28.740
It goes a long way in a sling underneath

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:30.180
the helicopter or sometimes in the bed

00:27:30.180 --> 00:27:32.240
of the helicopter in the back seat,

00:27:32.240 --> 00:27:34.520
but nestled in seat belts and, you know.

00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:35.630
And it's a long helicopter ride

00:27:35.630 --> 00:27:36.530
and bumpy and so forth.

00:27:36.530 --> 00:27:37.780
- [Harry] So you had one?

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:40.550
- No, that first year we had 1, 2, 3, 4.

00:27:40.550 --> 00:27:43.560
- But on this spotting and this siting

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:44.393
- That day

00:27:44.393 --> 00:27:46.620
- That day, so you were able
to take several back with you?

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:47.770
- The next day we found another one

00:27:47.770 --> 00:27:49.280
and about three days later
we found another one.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:51.330
It was like boom, boom, boom, boom, boom.

00:27:51.330 --> 00:27:56.330
Really rapid and it just was,
that week was just incredible,

00:27:56.628 --> 00:27:59.623
because we knew we had wonderful material.

00:28:03.823 --> 00:28:07.450
- At the site are you
carving him out of the rock

00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:09.813
or are you carving the rock and taking

00:28:09.813 --> 00:28:10.646
the whole magillah out?

00:28:10.646 --> 00:28:11.580
- Taking the whole magillah home.

00:28:11.580 --> 00:28:12.430
- Oh, yeah.

00:28:12.430 --> 00:28:14.169
- We don't carve them
out of the rock there.

00:28:14.169 --> 00:28:16.320
That is in the laboratory.

00:28:16.320 --> 00:28:18.420
Done under very controlled circumstances.

00:28:18.420 --> 00:28:20.770
You know, we're basically
bringing a bid boulder home.

00:28:20.770 --> 00:28:22.011
- With bones sticking out of it.

00:28:22.011 --> 00:28:23.610
And we just leave it.

00:28:23.610 --> 00:28:26.106
If the bone is showing,
we've already done too much,

00:28:26.106 --> 00:28:27.217
(chuckling) you know?

00:28:27.217 --> 00:28:29.924
And so we just try to
lightly work around it.

00:28:29.924 --> 00:28:31.480
Leaving a safety margin.

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:32.390
And you don't always get it right,

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:34.870
sometimes you do crack
a bone and so forth.

00:28:34.870 --> 00:28:35.703
- [Harry] Um hm

00:28:35.703 --> 00:28:37.600
- But that's okay, and
then you rough it out

00:28:37.600 --> 00:28:39.180
and back it comes to the laboratory.

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:41.775
It takes about a month
and a half to get home.

00:28:41.775 --> 00:28:45.210
- Now, I wanna understand how

00:28:45.210 --> 00:28:47.557
this discovery confirmed everything

00:28:47.557 --> 00:28:51.970
that you knew about where to
look and the king of rock.

00:28:51.970 --> 00:28:56.697
So this kind of rock was one that was,

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:06.330
such that the skeleton would
be partially visible, yeah?

00:29:06.330 --> 00:29:09.780
- These rocks were formed
in an ancient delta system.

00:29:09.780 --> 00:29:13.070
Part of the margins or the
bank of an ancient stream

00:29:13.070 --> 00:29:15.300
or a point bar, or some area that would

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:17.300
collect the skeletons as they washed

00:29:17.300 --> 00:29:19.510
down the stream in a flooding event

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:20.343
or something like that.

00:29:20.343 --> 00:29:21.770
And they were rapidly buried.

00:29:21.770 --> 00:29:25.020
That's a classic environment,
fossil environment

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:27.274
for preserving really nice bones.

00:29:27.274 --> 00:29:28.110
- [Harry] Mm hm

00:29:28.110 --> 00:29:29.630
- So it was clearly an ancient river

00:29:29.630 --> 00:29:31.227
and the margin of an ancient river.

00:29:31.227 --> 00:29:34.190
And this geologies perfect for that,

00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:36.330
to find lots of, and
there're other species

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:38.080
that are coming out of those rocks.

00:29:40.442 --> 00:29:44.543
- How did tiktaalik get his name?

00:29:44.543 --> 00:29:45.376
- Well what happened

00:29:45.376 --> 00:29:46.470
- [Harry] or her name?

00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:47.978
- I have no idea, his, her or whatever

00:29:47.978 --> 00:29:49.640
- Yeah (chuckles)

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:50.743
- I don't know.

00:29:50.743 --> 00:29:53.470
When we found this creature, you know,

00:29:53.470 --> 00:29:55.890
in the scientific paper it's
our job to give it a name,

00:29:55.890 --> 00:29:57.920
a generic and a specific name.

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:02.030
And we wanted the name to be meaningful

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:03.220
to the Inuit community.

00:30:03.220 --> 00:30:06.380
There was a Inuit community
about 200 miles away,

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:08.400
that was giving us
permits to work up there.

00:30:08.400 --> 00:30:09.850
We involved some of their youth

00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:11.787
in our field expeditions at the time.

00:30:11.787 --> 00:30:13.637
And we felt pretty connected to them.

00:30:14.560 --> 00:30:17.050
And we wanted them to feel involved

00:30:17.050 --> 00:30:19.340
in the project and in
our work and so forth.

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:24.340
So we worked with the Inuit
traditional knowledge elders.

00:30:24.479 --> 00:30:28.897
And we talked to them,
to come up with a name

00:30:28.897 --> 00:30:31.460
that is meaningful to them and to us

00:30:31.460 --> 00:30:32.680
and a name that we could pronounce.

00:30:32.680 --> 00:30:34.460
Now, Inuktitut is a
very difficult language

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:36.659
on the English speaking tongue.

00:30:36.659 --> 00:30:39.750
And so that was not an
easy thing. (chuckles)

00:30:39.750 --> 00:30:41.390
Those two parameters weren't always easy.

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:45.223
And so tiktaalik is their
word for fresh water fish.

00:30:46.740 --> 00:30:51.740
And the name stuck and the
species name is roseae, so.

00:30:52.048 --> 00:30:57.048
- So you take the tiktaalik
back to the laboratory

00:30:57.330 --> 00:30:59.830
and what do you find?

00:30:59.830 --> 00:31:02.492
Help us understand why this was

00:31:02.492 --> 00:31:06.886
such an important story
that made the cover,

00:31:06.886 --> 00:31:09.280
the front page of the New York Times.

00:31:09.280 --> 00:31:12.060
- Right, so, I wasn't the first person

00:31:12.060 --> 00:31:13.290
to see the beautiful material.

00:31:13.290 --> 00:31:14.970
Neither was Ted or any of the other

00:31:14.970 --> 00:31:16.910
senior scientists on the project.

00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:18.060
It was the fossil preparator.

00:31:18.060 --> 00:31:20.590
They're the talented people who

00:31:20.590 --> 00:31:24.210
literally sit with a needle and a pin vice

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:27.480
under a microscope, removing
the rock grain by grain.

00:31:27.480 --> 00:31:29.730
Now they can do this because the bone

00:31:29.730 --> 00:31:31.790
is harder than the rock.

00:31:31.790 --> 00:31:33.300
'cause the bone's kind of petrified.

00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:35.200
So there's a separation between the two.

00:31:35.200 --> 00:31:36.410
And so they use like little mini

00:31:36.410 --> 00:31:40.594
dental tools and pins and
so forth, over months.

00:31:40.594 --> 00:31:42.070
So we brought these things back

00:31:42.070 --> 00:31:43.850
and Fred Mullison in Philadelphia,

00:31:43.850 --> 00:31:46.360
Bob Masek in Chicago worked for months

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:49.000
removing the rock from the bone.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:50.000
- [Harry] Are these different fish

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:51.460
that they're working on, or

00:31:51.460 --> 00:31:52.820
- [ Other] Different titaalik specimens.

00:31:52.820 --> 00:31:53.653
- Yeah, yeah.

00:31:53.653 --> 00:31:55.130
- And so Bob was, we have a dinosaur lab

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:56.750
in Chicago that's really big so we had

00:31:56.750 --> 00:31:58.800
the big specimens of titaalik in Chicago.

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:00.230
There's a smaller lab in Philidelphia,

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:02.747
they're specialized for smaller stuff

00:32:02.747 --> 00:32:04.720
and so Fred was working
on the material there.

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:07.050
And over a period of
months, tiktaalik gradually

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:07.920
revealed itself, you know.

00:32:07.920 --> 00:32:10.470
First we saw the flat
head with the eyes on top

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:12.810
Then we saw that tiktaalik has a neck

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:14.920
then we saw the body with the scales

00:32:14.920 --> 00:32:17.750
on its back and fins, with fin webbing.

00:32:17.750 --> 00:32:19.980
Then Bob took apart one of the fins,

00:32:19.980 --> 00:32:20.910
took the fin webbing off.

00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:23.338
And in it we found, you
know, bones that correspond

00:32:23.338 --> 00:32:26.353
to shoulder, elbow and wrists.

00:32:26.353 --> 00:32:28.399
- [Harry] Mm hm

00:32:28.399 --> 00:32:30.350
- You know, over a
period of 5, 6, 7 months,

00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:32.330
this creature starting revealing itself

00:32:32.330 --> 00:32:34.980
as sort of a mosaic between fish

00:32:34.980 --> 00:32:37.040
and land living, limbed animal.

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:37.873
- [Harry] Mm hm

00:32:37.873 --> 00:32:40.250
- You know, if I was to hold
it in front of you right now,

00:32:40.250 --> 00:32:42.520
you would see is a creature
about four feet long.

00:32:42.520 --> 00:32:45.560
One of the smaller specimens.

00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:47.450
And you'd look at it and, you know,

00:32:47.450 --> 00:32:48.520
you'd see it has scales on its back

00:32:48.520 --> 00:32:49.510
and fins with fin webbing.

00:32:49.510 --> 00:32:50.760
You'd say, ah, fish.

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:52.290
Until you looked at the head.

00:32:52.290 --> 00:32:53.790
You'd see it has a crocodile like,

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:56.440
almost flat head with
eyes on top, has a neck.

00:32:56.440 --> 00:32:57.600
No fish has a neck.

00:32:57.600 --> 00:32:58.870
Then you'd see those limb bones

00:32:58.870 --> 00:33:01.260
that start to look awfully limb like.

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:02.370
Has big fat ribs.

00:33:02.370 --> 00:33:04.280
So it has this sort of mix between,

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:08.980
the characteristics of the
land living animals and fish.

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:11.070
Found at just the right
time in the fossil record

00:33:11.070 --> 00:33:12.930
at around 375 million years ago,

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:16.150
when we'd expect this
transition to be happening.

00:33:16.150 --> 00:33:19.743
- So, this discovery,

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:25.070
I wanna go, I'm fascinated
by the way in which

00:33:25.070 --> 00:33:26.350
all these things come together

00:33:26.350 --> 00:33:28.050
So, you're training.

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:30.200
Your knowledge of geology tells you

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:31.620
which rocks to look in

00:33:32.960 --> 00:33:35.530
and where to go.

00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:38.560
And your bringing all
your expertise to bear,

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:42.140
but an undergraduate who
happens to be on the team

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:43.460
discovers the site

00:33:43.460 --> 00:33:44.823
- Isn't that great

00:33:44.823 --> 00:33:47.900
- Yeah, yeah (both laughing)
and your perseverance

00:33:47.900 --> 00:33:50.800
says, oh, let's go back again at a time

00:33:50.800 --> 00:33:52.500
when you're debating whether to do that.

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:55.550
- Exactly, and you know,
but you bring your crew,

00:33:55.550 --> 00:33:56.840
each with different skills.

00:33:56.840 --> 00:33:58.160
And by the way, you have to cover

00:33:58.160 --> 00:33:59.470
a lot of turf up there

00:33:59.470 --> 00:34:01.210
- So you need a bunch of people looking,

00:34:01.210 --> 00:34:03.120
different kinds of eyes and so forth.

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:04.630
- By the way, Jason Downs, who was

00:34:04.630 --> 00:34:06.270
the undergraduate when this was found

00:34:06.270 --> 00:34:08.768
is now a post doctoral
fellow in paleontology.

00:34:08.768 --> 00:34:10.320
So he stuck with it.

00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:11.587
- [Harry] So he stuck
with it, yeah. (laughing)

00:34:11.587 --> 00:34:14.190
Having started off on a high note, yeah.

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:16.330
So he decided to go on.

00:34:16.330 --> 00:34:19.288
So, back to the fish.

00:34:19.288 --> 00:34:22.750
So, he has a neck, he or she has a neck.

