You know, look at doping scandals

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:41.403
and bicycling and baseball.

00:46:42.650 --> 00:46:44.390
Look at the technologies that can enhance

00:46:44.390 --> 00:46:47.930
human memory and muscle mass
and all basic parameters

00:46:47.930 --> 00:46:49.180
of what we are, you know.

00:46:50.123 --> 00:46:52.750
So, you come back in 500 years, I mean.

00:46:52.750 --> 00:46:55.558
Human performance will be
driven largely, I think

00:46:55.558 --> 00:46:58.020
by social structures and technologies

00:46:58.020 --> 00:46:59.273
that enhance them.

00:47:00.280 --> 00:47:04.690
- Does these discoveries in
these fields that you work in,

00:47:04.690 --> 00:47:06.880
in what way do they interface with the

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:08.870
global warming problem, if any at all?

00:47:08.870 --> 00:47:11.245
I mean, is it just that we get a sense of

00:47:11.245 --> 00:47:13.770
how it all, sorta fits together

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:18.550
and that at a certain point man has to

00:47:18.550 --> 00:47:21.900
draw a line as to what it wants to do

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:25.431
in certain directions least
it harm the environment?

00:47:25.431 --> 00:47:26.370
- Well, on the fossil record we see

00:47:26.370 --> 00:47:27.640
the influence of global warming.

00:47:27.640 --> 00:47:29.890
We see the influence of
global change in general

00:47:31.779 --> 00:47:34.340
on faunas and floras and
extinctions and so forth.

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:36.350
I mean, there's a finely tuned balance

00:47:36.350 --> 00:47:38.950
between changes in the
climate and the atmosphere

00:47:38.950 --> 00:47:43.804
and the kinds of life and their
distribution on our planet.

00:47:43.804 --> 00:47:46.850
What's challenging here
is the rate of change

00:47:46.850 --> 00:47:48.770
is not something we've
been able to measurer

00:47:48.770 --> 00:47:51.763
in the kind of fossil record
that I work on, easily.

00:47:53.266 --> 00:47:56.000
And so, it doesn't lend
us the predictive power

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:57.490
in the kinds of challenges
we're gonna face

00:47:57.490 --> 00:48:00.480
as a society as a result
of our own activities.

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:04.970
- Looking at, reflecting
on your career now,

00:48:04.970 --> 00:48:07.750
how would you advise
students who are interested

00:48:07.750 --> 00:48:10.590
in this stuff to prepare for the future?

00:48:10.590 --> 00:48:14.260
I mean, obviously become, develop skills

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:16.520
and a lot of discipline,
you've been saying.

00:48:16.520 --> 00:48:17.900
- Yeah, but it starts
with the liberal arts.

00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:18.733
It really does.

00:48:18.733 --> 00:48:20.630
You know, a good liberal
arts education can't be beat.

00:48:20.630 --> 00:48:21.463
You need it.

00:48:21.463 --> 00:48:22.296
It's an essential.

00:48:22.296 --> 00:48:25.202
Reading, writing, the
classics, literature,

00:48:25.202 --> 00:48:29.170
history, science, I mean
just a liberal education

00:48:29.170 --> 00:48:31.830
is the centerpiece for all
of this because that provides

00:48:31.830 --> 00:48:35.580
the grounding for your curiosity.

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:37.120
- Knowing, having a background that's

00:48:37.120 --> 00:48:38.730
sophisticated enough so that you know

00:48:38.730 --> 00:48:41.060
where to look when you have a question

00:48:41.060 --> 00:48:42.620
becomes so important.

00:48:42.620 --> 00:48:46.050
And not having fear, you
know to admit ignorance

00:48:46.923 --> 00:48:49.010
and ask a colleague and
go into a new field.

00:48:49.010 --> 00:48:51.030
I always encourage
students to be aggressive

00:48:51.030 --> 00:48:53.310
with their professors and their teachers.

00:48:53.310 --> 00:48:55.130
And sit and say, look I'm
interested in this stuff.

00:48:55.130 --> 00:48:57.130
What do I need to know,
how do I do it, you know.

00:48:57.130 --> 00:49:00.230
And they'll often be your best advisors.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:03.140
- How do think that, let's go back to your

00:49:03.140 --> 00:49:04.960
medical school class 'cause,

00:49:04.960 --> 00:49:08.920
How do you think you, with this background

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:11.030
have informed them

00:49:11.030 --> 00:49:15.690
and essentially, in
some way impacted their

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:21.680
educational experience and the way

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:26.540
they think about the
human body as a result of

00:49:28.226 --> 00:49:30.240
the broader perspective
that you bring to anatomy?

00:49:30.240 --> 00:49:32.440
- Well I like to think that, you know,

00:49:32.440 --> 00:49:34.013
at best my aspiration,
let's put it that way,

00:49:34.013 --> 00:49:36.110
is that they look at the
human body in a different way.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:38.800
Now they are in medical school
for a very particular reason.

00:49:38.800 --> 00:49:40.795
They need to know the
structures of the body

00:49:40.795 --> 00:49:43.470
and they need to have that tool kit,

00:49:43.470 --> 00:49:46.220
but along with that, I'd also love them

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:49.270
to have a appreciation of how important

00:49:49.270 --> 00:49:51.680
understanding our connections
to the rest of life

00:49:51.680 --> 00:49:54.501
are to understanding the human body.

00:49:54.501 --> 00:49:56.350
And I know for some medical students

00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:57.183
that's been very important.

00:49:57.183 --> 00:49:59.040
They've emailed me and
we've talked about it

00:49:59.040 --> 00:50:00.320
and you know, everybody's different.

00:50:00.320 --> 00:50:03.680
But, at least my aspiration
is absolutely that

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:06.330
knowing the connections we
have with the rest of life

00:50:06.330 --> 00:50:08.424
on our planet, not only tells us about

00:50:08.424 --> 00:50:11.470
the structures of our body,
but the ways our bodies

00:50:11.470 --> 00:50:14.410
are unintelligently
designed and they fall apart

00:50:14.410 --> 00:50:16.090
from time to time.

00:50:16.090 --> 00:50:19.850
- Well on that note, Neil,
I wanna thank you very much

00:50:19.850 --> 00:50:20.683
for being here.

